widely, including exploring Wong's thought on naturalism, criteria for moralities, the principle of charity, moral authority, and the concept of community, and looking at his readings of Xunzi and Zhuangzi. Wong's nuanced and forceful responses clarify and develop further arguments in his work. These engaging and critical exchanges between Wong and his critics illuminate not only Wong's thought, but also contemporary ethical theory and Chinese philosophy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aEthical relativism. 0aPhilosophy, Chinese. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Religion and Philosophy. 4aAsian Studies : Asian Studies. 4aPhilosophy : Comparative Philosophy. 4aPhilosophy : Ethics. 4aPhilosophy : Philosophy. 4aReligion and Spirituality : Religion. 7aPHILOSOPHY / Ethics & Moral Philosophy.2bisacsh1 aBloomfield, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBlum, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeisz, Steven F., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGowans, Christopher W., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHansen, Chad, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuang, Yong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHuang, Yong, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMassey, Daniel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSadler, Brook J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aXiao, Yang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aXiao, Yang, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUNY Press eBook Package 2014z978311149015140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978143